Data Sources

Europe map has been downloaded via the R package available on CRAN. For more information please visit https://ropengov.github.io/eurostat/.

More precisily, the geospatial data is downloaded from GISGO (http://ec.europa.eu/eurostat/web/gisco/geodata/reference-data/administrative-units-statistical-units) via the command .

Here below a simple procedure to install (if not present) and load the package:

if(require(eurostat) == FALSE){
  install.packages("eurostat")
  }else{
  library(eurostat)
  }

Once we download the data please remember to read the COPYRIGHT notice as indicated below.

Graphing external data sources on Europe map

The idea is to plot some indicators of CO concentrations for Europe, as provided in the AirPollution folder. CO concentration readings per country are stored in seperate csv files, one per each country. Records of CO concentrations range from the start to the end of year 2017. Therefore data at hand are time series. For the explorative analysis conducted in this quick study we would like to summarize the information on CO concentration for the overall year per each country via a single paramter, may it be concentrations averaged on the overall year or something similar. We therefore do not consider hereafter an analysis taking into account time-dependencies, seasonalities of the CO concentration etc. (It may be interesting to do so though).

First of all we need to enrich the euromap dataset with some codename for the countries. THe issue comes from the fact that the geospatial dataset has country names coded in orginal languages while in the AirPollution dataset countries are identified by short 2-character codes. The information we need is stored in the excel file .

(NB: AirPollution for UK does not exist in the folder. We have though data for Great Britain, i.e. GR. I simply use this data as proxy for all UK. On such basis I personally changed the file name GR_10_21117_2017_timeseries.csv to UK_10_21117_2017_timeseries.csv).

We now perform a operation in order to enrich the euromap dataset with the necessary codenames for a future link to the AirPollution data.

dic <- read.xlsx("dic.xlsx")
euromap <- left_join(euromap, dic %>% dplyr::select(Name, English_Name, Code_Name), by = c("NUTS_NAME" = "Name"))

Let’s review the dataset:

head(euromap)

Now we parse all the AirPollution files for which we have a corresponding region on the map. For example we have data on CO concentrations in Andorra but we do not have a key for Andorra in the geospatial dataset euromap. This means we cannot map the values of CO concentrations on the previous graph since we would need the latitudes and longitudes corresponding to Andorra, shortly speaking.

index_countries <- list.files("AirPollution/") %>% stringr::str_extract(.,pattern = "[A-z]{2}")
files_2_be_parsed <- list.files("AirPollution/")[index_countries  %in% unique(euromap$geo)]
index_countries <- index_countries[index_countries %in% unique(euromap$geo)]

Compute CO concentration per country in 2017, yearly averaged.

df_airpoll <- data.frame() 
for (i in seq_along(files_2_be_parsed)){
  
  df <- read.csv(paste0("AirPollution/",files_2_be_parsed[i]), fileEncoding = "UTF-16")
  df$DatetimeBegin <- as.Date(df$DatetimeBegin)
  df$DatetimeEnd <- as.Date(df$DatetimeEnd)
  df <- df %>% filter(AirPollutant == "CO") %>% 
    mutate(Year = year(DatetimeBegin), Month = month(DatetimeBegin)) %>%
    dplyr::select(Year, Month, Concentration, UnitOfMeasurement) %>%
    group_by(Year) %>%
    summarise(avg_CO_concentration_year= mean(Concentration)) %>%
    ungroup() %>%
    mutate(geo = index_countries[i])
  
  df_airpoll <- bind_rows(df_airpoll, df)  
  
}
euromap_1 <- left_join(euromap, df_airpoll, by = "geo")
europe_map_1 <- ggplot() +
  geom_polygon(data = euromap_1 %>% filter(lat > 27), 
               aes(x = long, y = lat, group = group, fill = avg_CO_concentration_year),
               color = 'black', size = .1) +
  xlab("Longitude \n GeoSpatial Source: (C) EuroGeographics for the administrative boundaries. \n
       https://ec.europa.eu/eurostat/web/gisco/geodata/reference-data/administrative-units-statistical-nits") +
  ylab("Latitude") +
  coord_map() +
  theme_bw() +
  scale_fill_continuous(name = "CO [mg/m3]",
                        breaks = seq(0,0.5,by = 0.05)) +
  ggtitle("2017-averaged CO concentrations")
europe_map_1

Compute CO concentrations per country in 2017, averaged by season.

We use 3-months windows as proxies for seasons. Winter being January-March, Spring April-June etc.

df_airpoll <- data.frame() 
for (i in seq_along(files_2_be_parsed)){
  
  df <- read.csv(paste0("AirPollution/",files_2_be_parsed[i]), fileEncoding = "UTF-16")
  df$DatetimeBegin <- as.Date(df$DatetimeBegin)
  df$DatetimeEnd <- as.Date(df$DatetimeEnd)
  df <- df %>% filter(AirPollutant == "CO") %>% 
    mutate(Year = year(DatetimeBegin), Month = month(DatetimeBegin)) %>%
    rowwise() %>%
    mutate(Season = c("winter","spring","summer","autumn")[first(which(Month <= c(3,6,9,12)))])
  df <- df %>%
    dplyr::select(Year, Month, Concentration, UnitOfMeasurement, Season) %>%
    group_by(Year, Season) %>%
    summarise(avg_season_CO_concentration= mean(Concentration)) %>%
    ungroup() %>%
    mutate(geo = index_countries[i])
  
  df_airpoll <- bind_rows(df_airpoll, df)  
  
}

Let’s enrich the dataset:

euromap_2 <- left_join(euromap, df_airpoll, by = "geo")

Winter:

europe_map_winter <- ggplot() +
  geom_polygon(data = euromap_2 %>% filter(lat > 27 & Season %in% c("winter",NA)), 
               aes(x = long, y = lat, group = group, fill = avg_season_CO_concentration),
               color = 'black', size = .1) +
  xlab("Longitude \n GeoSpatial Source: (C) EuroGeographics for the administrative boundaries. \n
       https://ec.europa.eu/eurostat/web/gisco/geodata/reference-data/administrative-units-statistical-nits") +
  ylab("Latitude") +
  coord_map() +
  theme_bw() +
  scale_fill_continuous(name = "CO [mg/m3]",
                        breaks = seq(0,0.8,by = 0.075)) +
  ggtitle("2017 averaged CO concentration in January-March")

               aes(x = long, y = lat, group = group, fill = avg_season_CO_concentration),
               color = 'black', size = .1) +
  xlab("Longitude \n GeoSpatial Source: (C) EuroGeographics for the administrative boundaries. \n
       https://ec.europa.eu/eurostat/web/gisco/geodata/reference-data/administrative-units-statistical-nits") +

  coord_map() +

europe_map_summer

NB SOMETHING IS PRETTY CURIOUS ABOUT ALBANIA. Super high concentrations also in summer (relative to the other countries) maybe it requires some investigation. For the time being the analysis excludes Albanie from the AirPollution folder. In order to so we have changed the name of the csv file from AL_10_34828_2017_timeseries.csv to EXCLUDED_AL_10_34828_2017_timeseries.csv. In such case the first two letters of the file EX do not match any kind of country so automatically the data from Albanie is not parsed.
